## 3. The Prompt Contract (generic skeleton)

Every prompt, whatever the mode, fills these slots. The mode-specific skeletons below are specializations of this one.

```text
<path-variable header from section 2>

Context: <one or two lines: which {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} / file / goal>.
Task: <the single change to make>.
Edit scope: <files that may change>. Read-only: <files that must not change>.
Constraints: <relevant OCs by id>.
Deliverable: <what to produce, and where under ${CLAUDE_DIR}/{TASK_ID}/>.
Verification: <command to run / output to inspect / criterion to meet>.
<!-- if:ENABLE_PUBLISH_STEP=yes -->Publish: after Verification passes, commit + push the docs repo (see the Publish section).<!-- endif -->
```

`TASK_ID` is `YYYYMMDD-HHMM-XXXX`, with the timestamp resolved by a real `date` call at generation time (never a placeholder), so the audit chain holds. See `docs/operations/directory-map.md`.

## 4. Mode-Specific Skeletons

Investigate, Design, and Write are usually done in Claude Chat and rarely need a Claude Code prompt. The modes below do.

### 4.1 Implement (SRC)

```text
<header>
Context: implement <change> for {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} <id>.
Task: <the one source change>. Gate it behind a flag, default OFF, so the
  default path is unchanged (bit-identical) until explicitly enabled.
Edit scope: <specific source files>. Read-only: everything else.
Constraints: OC-2 (source read-only outside scope), OC-5 (brace paths), OC-7 (state sync).
Deliverable: the patch + a one-line summary of what changed and what stayed identical.
Verification: <import/build succeeds>; with the flag OFF, <a baseline check> is unchanged.
```

### 4.2 Experiment (RUN, then record)

```text
<header>
Context: run {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} <id>; success criteria are locked in
  docs/project/project-status.md.
Task: run <command/config>. Do not change source. Write outputs to a NEW dir distinct
  from prior {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} outputs.
Read-only: all source and prior results.
Deliverable: the result files + the metrics, under ${CLAUDE_DIR}/{TASK_ID}/outputs/.
Verification: each locked criterion judged mechanically against its threshold.
```
Recording the result into the docs is the closing step of Experiment mode (see `docs/operations/session-kickoff.md`): numbers to `docs/evaluation/comparison.md`, verdict + next task to `docs/project/project-status.md`, a row to `docs/project/themes/theme-index.md` and a body to `docs/project/themes/theme-bodies.md`, lever state to `docs/method/algorithmic-levers.md`; then `make docs-check`<!-- if:ENABLE_PUBLISH_STEP=yes -->, and Publish (commit + push the docs repo; see the Publish section)<!-- endif -->.

### 4.3 Analyze

```text
<header>
Context: <question to answer> from existing artifacts at <paths>.
Task: analyze read-only. Existing files must not change; write only under ${CLAUDE_DIR}/{TASK_ID}/.
Deliverable: outputs/analysis_report.md (data separate from interpretation; confidence levels).
Verification: include the critical-verification pass from docs/operations/analysis-mode.md
  (state the claim, try to refute it, report what survives).
```

### 4.4 Result Ingestion (when a result lands without a fresh run)

```text
<header>
Ingest the result at <path>. Do not re-run the experiment. Update, in order:
docs/evaluation/comparison.md (numbers), docs/project/project-status.md (verdict, next task),
docs/project/themes/theme-index.md (+ body in theme-bodies.md), docs/method/algorithmic-levers.md
(lever state). Then run make docs-check.
<!-- if:ENABLE_PUBLISH_STEP=yes -->Then Publish: commit + push the docs repo (see the Publish section).<!-- endif -->
```

### 4.5 Docs Update

```text
<header>
Change class: <from docs/operations/consistency-guard.md>.
Edit first: <file>. Cascade: <files from entrypoint section 5>.
Run make docs-check from the docs repo and report the result before finishing.
<!-- if:ENABLE_PUBLISH_STEP=yes -->Then Publish: commit + push the docs repo so the doc updates land upstream (see the Publish section).<!-- endif -->
```

## 5. A Worked Example (illustrative)

A filled-in Implement prompt for a generic "add a gated alternative objective" change:

```text
<path-variable header>
Context: implement an alternative training objective for {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} 7.
Task: add a function `alt_objective(...)` and a flag `--objective={default,alt}` (default
  `default`). With `default`, behavior is bit-identical to today.
Edit scope: {{PROJECT_VAR_BRACE}}/src/objective.py, {{PROJECT_VAR_BRACE}}/src/options.py.
  Read-only: everything else.
Constraints: OC-2, OC-5, OC-7. Subtract-first: reuse the existing loss plumbing, add no new module.
Deliverable: the patch + a note confirming the default path is unchanged.
Verification: `python -c "import src.objective"` succeeds; a 1-step run with `--objective=default`
  produces the same loss value as before (paste both).
```

## 6. Prompt Smells (anti-patterns)

- **No edit scope** -> the executor refactors files you did not mean to touch.
- **Two changes in one prompt** -> you cannot attribute the result to either. Split them.
- **"Improve X"** with no criterion -> there is nothing to verify. State the target.
- **Numbers or paths from memory** -> stale. Verify with rg / view first.
- **Add-first** ("also add a helper just in case") -> bias and dead code. Subtract first.
- **No verification step** -> you are trusting, not checking. Always give one.

## 7. Verification Ladder

Match the verification cost to the change: (1) it imports / builds; (2) a tiny dry-run executes; (3) the default path is unchanged when a new option is off; (4) a small fixed subset gives the expected metric; (5) the full criterion is met. Ask for the cheapest rung that actually proves the claim.

