## Publish (optional closing step)

This step is opt-in (config `ENABLE_PUBLISH_STEP=yes`). It applies to any task whose result should land in the git docs repo -- a documentation edit, a recorded result, or (when the src mirror is on) refreshed source. Append a `Publish:` line to the prompt so the executor commits and pushes *after Verification passes*. It stages the repo's tracked content, so one commit captures your documentation edits and, if the mirror is enabled, the `src/` mirror:

```text
Publish: once Verification passes, publish to the git docs repo:
  cd {{REPO_VAR_BRACE}} \
    && make docs-check && make sync-src \
    && git add -A -- . ':(exclude)*.rp-new' \
    && (git diff --cached --quiet || git commit -m "<TASK_ID>: <one-line summary>") \
    && git push origin HEAD
```

- Push only the docs repo {{REPO_VAR_BRACE}} -- never the workspace {{PROJECT_VAR_BRACE}}.
- Guard first: `make docs-check` aborts the publish on failure (the `&&` chain stops) and is never bypassed.
- `make sync-src` refreshes the read-only `src/` mirror from {{PROJECT_VAR_BRACE}}/src (a no-op unless the source mirror is enabled).
- The `:(exclude)*.rp-new` pathspec keeps unreviewed `*.rp-new` merge artifacts out of the commit, and the commit runs only when something is staged ("nothing to commit" is normal, not a failure).
- `git push origin HEAD` needs `origin` with an upstream -- init creates neither, so push once with `git push -u origin <branch>` first. Report any push failure (auth, conflict, no upstream); do not swallow it.
- After the push, refresh the Claude Project's connected source so the {{ROLE_TERM}} reads the new commit -- Chat serves a snapshot, and a push alone does not update it. Remind {{USER_NAME}} of this in the prompt's result note.
